		<item>
			<title>Focusing &amp; Digital-Back Module</title>
			<link>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/focusing--digital-back.html</link>
			<description>
				&lt;div class="article-summary"&gt;&lt;p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana;"&gt;Screws on the top of the module back module connecting this portion to the focusing module. As such, one could make a variety of backs that mount to different cameras, or even design their own film-progression mechanism.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
			</description>
			<pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2014 23:32:44 +0100</pubDate>
			<guid>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/focusing--digital-back.html</guid>
            <enclosure url="https://pascoli.github.io/_Media/hackathon-winners-8_med.jpeg" length="1967095" type="image/jpeg"></enclosure>
			
		</item>
		<item>
			<title>Solenoid Circuitry</title>
			<link>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/solenoid-circuitry.html</link>
			<description>
				&lt;div class="article-summary"&gt;&lt;p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana;"&gt;The 4 pin dip-switch provides the camera with 16 different exposure speeds (up to about 1/500th of a second). When the button is pressed, the solenoid is triggered and the shutter opens and closes.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
			</description>
			<pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2014 23:32:44 +0100</pubDate>
			<guid>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/solenoid-circuitry.html</guid>
            <enclosure url="https://pascoli.github.io/_Media/hackathon-winners-10_med.jpeg" length="2305833" type="image/jpeg"></enclosure>
			
		</item>
