		<item>
			<title>Overview</title>
			<link>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/overview.html</link>
			<description>
				&lt;div class="article-summary"&gt;&lt;p style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0);"&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 14px; font-family: Verdana;"&gt;On top you can see the circuit (arduino, op-amp, dip-switch, and push-button) that controls the shutter mechanism. Farthest to the right is the lens-aperture-shutter module. In the middle is the focusing module (this module is stationary and the first module slides in-and-out to focus). The largest wooden rectangular prism (on the left) is the film/digital-back module, which in this instance connects to my Nikon d90.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/div&gt;
			</description>
			<pubDate>Mon, 10 Feb 2014 22:56:09 +0100</pubDate>
			<guid>https://pascoli.github.io/undergraduate-engineering/modular-camera/overview.html</guid>
            <enclosure url="https://pascoli.github.io/_Media/hackathon-winners-1_med.jpeg" length="2055060" type="image/jpeg"></enclosure>
			
		</item>
